01:02:12,050 --> 01:02:13,270
Scott: That's the one with the group scan, right?

1202
01:02:13,350 --> 01:02:13,591
Rym: Yes.

1203
01:02:13,872 --> 01:02:14,435
Rym: Flexibility.

1204
01:02:14,455 --> 01:02:15,500
Rym: There are three codes here.

1205
01:02:15,701 --> 01:02:17,590
Rym: No code for a classy springy boom.

1206
01:02:18,270 --> 01:02:19,716
Rym: I for a very flexible boom.

1207
01:02:20,118 --> 01:02:23,050
Rym: Or X for a flexible boom and a springy ear section.

1208
01:02:23,691 --> 01:02:26,970
Rym: And then paragraphs of description of what each one of these is.

1209
01:02:27,030 --> 01:02:28,857
Scott: So why would you even need one or the other, right?

1210
01:02:29,239 --> 01:02:31,970
Scott: This is the boom that goes from the ear to your face, right?

1211
01:02:32,330 --> 01:02:36,490
Scott: You would want one that is where you can bend it and it stays in the shape that you bend it to.

1212
01:02:36,832 --> 01:02:36,933
Rym: Ah.

1213
01:02:37,033 --> 01:02:38,061
Rym: So here's the explanation.

1214
01:02:38,101 --> 01:02:39,250
Rym: Just to give you an example.

1215
01:02:39,632 --> 01:02:43,850
Rym: The classic E6 is a good choice when one person alone will wear the microphone.

1216
01:02:44,451 --> 01:02:45,240
Rym: It holds its shape.

1217
01:02:45,301 --> 01:02:45,989
Rym: Just put it on and go.

1218
01:02:46,710 --> 01:02:54,890
Rym: The eye is highly flexible with the larger silicone rubber piece to use when multiple people share the mic and you have to reconfigure it on the fly for different people.

1219
01:02:55,050 --> 01:02:58,050
Scott: Oh, so the first one you reshape it and it stays in that shape forever?

1220
01:02:58,352 --> 01:02:58,730
Rym: Basically.

1221
01:02:58,970 --> 01:03:01,170
Scott: The other one you can keep reshaping a bunch.

1222
01:03:01,450 --> 01:03:04,029
Rym: And then the flex is a compromise between those two.

1223
01:03:04,670 --> 01:03:07,290
Rym: For like theater, you might have to fuck with it occasionally.

1224
01:03:09,414 --> 01:03:12,830
Scott: Sure, the first one you can shape it once and leave it that shape forever.

1225
01:03:13,291 --> 01:03:14,010
Scott: You can reshape it.

1226
01:03:14,010 --> 01:03:16,188
Scott: But why not just get the reshaping one always?

1227
01:03:16,450 --> 01:03:20,870
Rym: Because the reshaping one will possibly lose its shape over the course of doing something.

1228
01:03:21,392 --> 01:03:23,569
Rym: And you have to refit it to your head every time you put it on.

1229
01:03:24,191 --> 01:03:25,630
Scott: Oh, it sort of loses its shape.

1230
01:03:25,911 --> 01:03:27,350
Rym: The classic, like you do a thing and then it's set.

1231
01:03:27,350 --> 01:03:29,490
Scott: The other one is really firm and stays that way forever.

1232
01:03:29,630 --> 01:03:30,315
Rym: Exactly.

1233
01:03:30,335 --> 01:03:32,389
Rym: It stays that way for as long as you need it to.

1234
01:03:33,192 --> 01:03:34,819
Scott: But it can be reshaped.

1235
01:03:34,940 --> 01:03:36,568
Scott: But if you reshape it too much, it's going to break?

1236
01:03:37,090 --> 01:03:37,581
Scott: I don't know.

1237
01:03:38,190 --> 01:03:39,902
Scott: Yeah, why not get just that one always?

1238
01:03:39,922 --> 01:03:41,010
Scott: Or the compromise one?

1239
01:03:41,010 --> 01:03:46,130
Rym: So what if you own it for a venue where you have a different person speaking every night?

1240
01:03:47,650 --> 01:03:54,770
Scott: If that firm one can be reshaped a bunch without breaking and it holds its shape once I shape it, why not use that one?

1241
01:03:54,870 --> 01:03:55,978
Rym: It's not easy to shape.

1242
01:03:55,998 --> 01:03:57,810
Rym: I watch videos on how to shape it.

1243
01:03:57,810 --> 01:03:58,317
Scott: It's not just like you.

1244
01:03:58,337 --> 01:03:59,269
Scott: don't just bend it and that's it?

1245
01:03:59,611 --> 01:03:59,692
Rym: No.

1246
01:03:59,732 --> 01:04:03,490
Rym: You like flex and pull and the idea is that you make it perfect for one person.

1247
01:04:03,650 --> 01:04:04,429
Rym: Leave it that way forever.

1248
01:04:04,775 --> 01:04:04,990
Rym: Alright.

1249
01:04:05,150 --> 01:04:05,963
Rym: That's what it's aimed for.

1250
01:04:06,592 --> 01:04:08,001
Scott: Because that matters that much, right?

1251
01:04:08,042 --> 01:04:09,250
Scott: If it's a little bit out of place.

1252
01:04:09,874 --> 01:04:11,290
Rym: At these volumes, it kind of does.

1253
01:04:12,010 --> 01:04:12,596
Rym: So pattern.

1254
01:04:12,717 --> 01:04:13,990
Rym: Omnidirectional or directional?

1255
01:04:14,130 --> 01:04:17,650
Scott: Well, it's always being worn on someone's head pointing at their mouth.

1256
01:04:17,731 --> 01:04:20,490
Scott: So why wouldn't you always want it to point straight at the mouth and that's it?

1257
01:04:21,151 --> 01:04:23,550
Rym: Well, usually actually you want omnidirectional for these things.

1258
01:04:23,933 --> 01:04:24,259
Scott: Okay.

1259
01:04:24,300 --> 01:04:24,829
Scott: Why is that?

1260
01:04:25,210 --> 01:04:26,901
Rym: Because it's usually not pointed at your mouth.

1261
01:04:26,962 --> 01:04:28,169
Rym: It's just near your mouth.

1262
01:04:28,690 --> 01:04:31,570
Rym: And omnidirectionals don't fuck with the sound.

1263
01:04:31,870 --> 01:04:34,410
Rym: Directional microphones actually do fuck with your sound a little bit.

1264
01:04:35,093 --> 01:04:38,330
Rym: And they also, if they get a little out of place, now you're fucked.

1265
01:04:39,691 --> 01:04:41,910
Scott: Why would you then ever want the directional one?

1266
01:04:42,350 --> 01:04:45,930
Rym: So you and me on a stage, we probably want omnis because it's just us talking.

1267
01:04:46,550 --> 01:04:50,830
Rym: What if we're on a stage singing with Britney Spears and there's tons of noise on stage?

1268
01:04:51,255 --> 01:04:52,190
Rym: Then we need a directional.

1269
01:04:52,870 --> 01:04:56,510
Scott: Oh, so that the guitars jamming and such don't go into the microphones?

1270
01:04:58,410 --> 01:04:58,810
Scott: Alright.

1271
01:04:59,471 --> 01:05:01,266
Rym: And then there's all these different types of directionality.

1272
01:05:01,286 --> 01:05:01,770
Rym: We'll skip all that.

1273
01:05:01,870 --> 01:05:02,410
Rym: We'll go with the omni.

1274
01:05:02,992 --> 01:05:04,377
Rym: So, sensitivity.

